Customers are disgustingly rude
McDonalds Crew Member (Current Employee) - Telford - May 14, 2021
I’ve been working at McDonald’s for a year and 7 months now and for a 17 year old college student like myself it is a good place to work in terms of pay, benefits, flexibility and experience. When I was first employed I enjoyed the job however about a year in I noticed I was feeling exhausted and upset at the mere thought of going into work. Customers treat you disgustingly and have no ounce of respect. They ruined the whole experience for me and I can find myself going home in tears after the way they treat me. Management never do anything to stop it and head office continue to introduce new and stupid ideas e.g. Uber eats, click and serve that will bring more money in but cause more stress and anger amongst staff. Some managers are good hard workers who work alongside staff however some are lazy and really don’t care about you until it’s their legal obligation. Although I am appreciative for the experience and good pay I receive I am at this point counting down the days until I can quit which is all down to how horrible customers are to you and that’s the plain truth.
Pros
Free meals, benefits, pay, flexibility
Cons
Long hours, exhausting, horrible treatment from customers.
Was this review helpful?

Stressful fast paced environment
Crew Member (Current Employee) - Middlesbrough - April 23, 2021
The work environment can be fast paced and stressful depending on how popular the store is you are working at. management will patronise you and treat you like a child no matter how long you have worked there or how well you know the job, you will be asked to do tasks that you are in the middle of doing so that management can look good to salaried managers and you will be given shifts out of your availability because schedule runners will actively ignore your requests and tell you you put them in too late
Pros
Free lunch up to 4 menu items
Cons
Zero hour contract, You will be asked to perform tasks that are above your pay rate for the same amount, you would normally earn, you will be given hours out of your availability and asked to try and get rid of them yourself

Fun workplace, stressful work
Crew Member (Current Employee) - Farnborough - April 23, 2021
Working at Mcdonald's can be a fun environment, collages are great and everyone gets along. However, the work itself can be stressful as you could go from hardly any orders to a large amount with a small amount of time to actually prepare the order. Some stations are easier than others, for example completing drinks and desserts can be easier when the restaurant is quieter but every day there will be a period of time where you are stressed as a result of customers continuously coming to the restaurant and buying large orders. Hops this helps with your decision to work here.
Pros
Free Lunch, discount when not working
Cons
Long hours, can be stressful, dealing with angry customers.

Crew Member (Former Employee) - Swansea, Swansea - April 22, 2021
Working here was an okay experience for the first 3 weeks of the probationary period but after the 3 weeks were up it went down hill fast. It turned out not to be a fun environment to work in, some of the managers were sound however there were a few occassions where they would say I was doing a good job and then go behind my back to the higher ups saying I wasn't pulling my weight. The most enjoyable part of the job was unfortunately when my shift had ended and I could go home - for a first job it wasn't too bad but staying long term would not be (and wasn't going to be) an option that I would have considered.

Fun place to work
Shift Manager (Former Employee) - Northampton - April 21, 2021
McDonald’s is a great starting point in anyone’s career. You can make a lot of lovely new friends and the job is quite easy to learn if you put your mind to it. You have to be able to work fast and be willing to learn. It’s very easy to get promoted if you work hard which then means pay rises which is a bonus. Management isn’t the best at times and a lot of them tend to be lazy the higher up they go which is frustrating when you are struggling and the rotas aren’t the best as they are always posted with such short notice
Pros
Free lunch, ok pay, discounted food, good environment
Cons
Long hours, poor management, bad rota

Very busy & fast paced environment but helps you multitask
Crew Member (Current Employee) - Princes road, dartford - April 21, 2021
A fast paced environment where you need to be working all the time. You will definitly improve your multitasking and listening skills, as orders for your work comes continuosly and you need to be organaized.
Shifts can be hectic or calm depending on the managers and busy days. I had a pleasant experience at princes road, dartford mcdonalds.
Managers were very caring and teammates would be assisting you and helping you out always. Good teamwork among all employees.
Only negative would be slight body pain at first cos you will be standing and working continously thru out ur shift.
Pros
Free food and unlimited drinks. Caring managers and employees. Can acquire new skills
Cons
Gets physicaly tired easily. Parttime preffered. Too busy and fast environment

Fun workplace make loads of friends but
Crew Member (Former Employee) - Scotland - April 16, 2021
I started McDonald’s as a full time job before my college course started which was also full time. So I thought that I would be able to have some flexibility around my college into work when I started but I felt like that wasn’t the case I had many meetings for my availability and mentioning the days I physically couldn’t work, which wasn’t taken note very well considering I still was made to come in. I would’ve had to phone in to ask to get my shift covered/ or even phone in sick to have some time to focus on my college work but I wouldn’t have a choice I’d still get made to make it and get a warning for not being “organised”. One of the managers even said that I needed to prioritise McDonald’s over my college! As it was more important. I felt like I was treated unfairly and that I had no outside life other than being on shift constantly. If you are planning on working, just Be aware of having no time out out with work. The only positive things I’d honestly give out of this job was that I met lots of amazing people on shift and that it gave me more confident skills in customer service. Just a shame on the management side really
Pros
Free lunches, make lots of new friends
Cons
No outside life, management treated you poorly.

Good place to work
McDonalds Crew Member (Current Employee) - Manchester, Greater Manchester - April 12, 2021
I’ve worked at Mcdonald’s for 18 months now and whilst the flexibility of shifts is strange (meaning you can have one shift one week and 5 the next), it’s a good place to work, especially as a teenager/young adult for your first job as most people there are young themselves. I wouldn’t recommend mcdonald’s if you want a liveable wage because of the uncertainty of shifts. it can become a bit of a joke when they have you on a 2-10 one day and a 9-5 the next because it doesn’t leave you with any time for yourself and socialising. the people who work at mcdonald’s tend to have fun personalities, although the majority of people still act like they’re in high school but you learn to get along with it anyway.
Pros
easy to make friends
Cons
uncertainty of shifts and pay
Was this review helpful?

Flexible but immature environment
Team Member (Former Employee) - Crewe, Cheshire - April 12, 2021
Worked there under a year and have dealt with managers who belittles you in front of customers & colleagues. A lot of favouritism seems to be going on from the managers and when I started as a newbie, managers laughed at me with their ‘favourites’ (for not knowing somethings that I haven’t been trained to do) instead of offering assistance. Another thing is noticing how two faced & childish people are so if you’re an introvert and who minds your own business then this place is not for you!

On a high note, I have met some people who are genuinely kind and willing to help you no matter what and from working there, I’ve learned & discovered new skills that might come in handy in the near future.
Pros
Free lunches & flexible shifts
Cons
toxic environment & Unprofessional management team
